er.bind(channel=self.name)\n    73\t```\n    74\t\n    75\t---\n    76\t\n    77
\t## 2. Branch naming\n    78\t\n    79\t### §2.1 Format\n    80\t\n    81\t`<ty
pe>/<short-desc>`\n    82\t\n    83\t| type | Use |\n    84\t|---|---|\n    85\t
| `feat` | New feature |\n    86\t| `fix` | Bug fix |\n    87\t| `refactor` | Re
factor (not a feature, not a bug fix) |\n    88\t| `perf` | Performance |\n    8
9\t| `chore` | Misc (deps bump, doc structure, etc.) |\n    90\t| `docs` | Docs 
only |\n    91\t| `test` | Tests only |\n    92\t\n    93\t`short-desc`: **snake
_case**, English, 3–5 words describing the change.\n    94\t\n    95\t| ✅ Good 
| ❌ Bad |\n    96\t|---|---|\n    97\t| `feat/whatsapp_lid_mapping` | `feat/优
化` |\n    98\t| `fix/cron_dst_transition` | `bugfix` |\n    99\t| `refactor/cli
_cron_sentinel` | `huangjie-test` |\n   100\t| `chore/upgrade_uv` | `tmp` |\n   
101\t\n   102\t### §2.2 Confirm the base before cutting\n   103\t\n   104\t- Bef
ore cutting any branch (`fix` / `feat` / `refactor` / anything), **ask the user 
which base to cut from** — don\'t pick one silently.\n   105\t- If unspecified, 
default to **`main`** (the integration branch).\n   106\t- Flow: `git fetch orig
in main`, then cut from the latest tip.\n   107\t- Combined with the branch-firs
t rule: **confirm base + cut the branch, then start editing** — never write on a
working branch and carve the branch out afterwards.\n   108\t\n   109\t---\n   1
10\t\n   111\t## 3. Commits (Conventional Commits)\n   112\t\n   113\t### §3.1 M
essage format\n   114\t\n   115\t```\n   116\t<type>(<scope>): <subject>\n   117
\t\n   118\t<body — optional>\n   119\t\n   120\t<footer — optional>\n   121\t``
`\n   122\t\n   123\t**type** — same set as §2.1, plus 3 commit-only types:\n   
124\t\n   125\t| type | Meaning |\n   126\t|---|---|\n   127\t| `feat` | New fea
ture |\n   128\t| `fix` | Bug fix |\n   129\t| `docs` | Docs only |\n   130\t| `
refactor` | Refactor |\n   131\t| `perf` | Performance |\n   132\t| `test` | Tes
ts only |\n   133\t| `build` | Build system / external deps |\n   134\t| `ci` | 
CI config |\n   135\t| `chore` | Other misc |\n   136\t| `revert` | Revert a pri
or commit |\n   137\t\n   138\t**scope** — a top-level subpackage of `raven/`. S
ee the `Repo layout` section of `README.md` for the canonical list. Spanning mul
tiple scopes → omit the scope, or use `(*)`.\n   139\t\n   140\t**subject** — lo
wercase start; ≤ 72 chars; no trailing period; English.\n   141\t\n   142\t**foo
ter** (optional):\n   143\t- `BREAKING CHANGE: <desc>` — triggers a MAJOR bump o
nce public;\n   144\t- `Closes #123` — auto-closes the issue on merge.\n   145\t
\n   146\t### §3.1.1 Top rule: the whole message is English (subject + body + fo
oter)\n   147\t\n   148\tNo other languages anywhere in the message — not just t
he subject; body and footer too.\n   149\t\n   150\t| Part | Rule |\n   151\t|--
-|---|\n   152\t| subject | English, lowercase start, ≤ 72 chars, no period |\n 
 153\t| body | **All English**; when citing a non-English plan / discussion, **t
ranslate** it, don\'t paste |\n   154\t| punctuation | **ASCII-only** — not just
no full-width punctuation (`：`,`，`,`。`,`「」`,`""` …) but also no em-dash `—`
, curly quotes, or ellipsis `…` (all non-ASCII, all rejected by CI); no `§`-numb
ering, no non-English path names; the latin part of a §N.M anchor is fine |\n   
155\t| trailer | `Co-authored-by: ...` is ASCII by format |\n   156\t\n   157\t*
*Why:** Conventional-Commits tooling (commitlint / semantic-release / changelog 
generators) parses ASCII grammar and mis-lints on non-English text; cross-langua
ge reviewers and a public commit history both need English.\n   158\t\n   159\t*
*Process:**\n   160\t1. **Before writing:** translate the points in your head to
English first — don\'t write a non-English body then translate (that leaves full
-width residue).\n   161\t2. **After writing:** self-check with `git log -1`; an
y non-English char → rewrite.\n   162\t3. **Already committed but violating:** r
ewrite the message with `git rebase -i` **only after explicit user authorization
**; don\'t rewrite history unprompted (see §3.4).\n   163\t\n   164\t### §3.2 ✅
Good / ❌ Bad\n   165\t\n   166\t✅ Good:\n   167\t\n   168\t```\n   169\tfeat(c
li): rename cron show/remove to get/delete\n   170\tfix(channels): default allow
_from to [\'*\'] instead of deny-all\n   171\trefactor(cli): replace --cron-expr
with --cron and --every-seconds with --every\n   172\t```\n   173\t\n   174\t❌ 
Bad:\n   175\t- `更新代码` (non-English + no type/scope);\n   176\t- `update` (n
o type/scope);\n   177\t- `feat: Cron 命令重命名为 get 和 delete.` (uppercase + 
period + non-English + no scope).\n   178\t\n   179\t### §3.3 Trailer rules (com
mit message + PR description)\n   180\t\n   181\t**✅ Required:**\n   182\t\n   
183\t- `Co-authored-by: Claude (<model-id>) <noreply@anthropic.com>` — when Clau
de helped write the code, append it at the end of the commit body (blank line ab
ove), or at the end of the PR description.\n   184\t  - `<model-id>` = the **act
ual current-session model ID** (e.g. `claude-opus-4-8` / `claude-sonnet-4-6` / `
claude-haiku-4-5`), not a placeholder. The model version keeps per-model contrib
ution distinguishable.\n   185\t  - Format follows the aider convention; GitHub 
renders `Co-authored-by` as a co-author on the commit / PR.\n   186\t- Multiple 
co-authors → one per line, standard git trailer format (`Name <email>`).\n   187
\t- The repo **squash-merges** PRs (rebase only freshens the branch before push;
the merge collapses the branch to one commit on `main`). The squash commit\'s su
bject is the PR title and its body is the **PR description** (`squash_merge_comm
it_message=PR_BODY`) — individual commit bodies are dropped. GitHub still auto-c
ollects each commit\'s `Co-authored-by` into the squash commit, so keep the trai
ler in your commit and put `Closes #NNN` + reviewer context in the PR descriptio
n (that is what lands on `main`).\n   188\t\n   189\t**❌ Don\'t add:**\n   190\
t- `Refs: ...` pointing at locally-visible-only / git-ignored paths (invisible t
o others);\n   191\t- `🤖 Generated with Claude Code` and similar emoji banners 
— `Co-authored-by` already conveys co-authorship (and is the structured, machine
-readable attribution); a marketing badge adds no attribution value;\n   192\t- 
internal commit-hash references / temporary branch names — docs/PRs describe the
present state only.\n   193\t\n   194\t### §3.4 Hard rule: when to commit\n   19
5\t\n   196\t- **Don\'t commit unprompted** — only when the user explicitly says
"commit" / "提交" / "save".\n   197\t- "Commit per phase" written in a plan is *
*not** pre-authorization — a plan is a reference; committing still needs the use
r\'s word.\n   198\t- After finishing a phase, **report and stop**; wait for acc
eptance + an explicit commit instruction.\n   199\t- **Don\'t** `git commit --am
end` a prior commit (unless the user explicitly asks to amend).\n   200\t- If a 
pre-commit hook fails, create a **new** commit to fix it — don\'t amend.\n   201
\t\n   202\t### §3.5 Sync before push + force-push boundary\n   203\t\n   204\t*
*Rule:** before pushing a feature branch, base it on the **latest `main`**.\n   
205\t\n   206\t| Step | Command | Note |\n   207\t|---|---|---|\n   208\t| 1. Sy
nc remote | `git fetch origin <target>` | Doesn\'t touch the working tree |\n   
209\t| 2. Dry-run conflicts | `git merge-tree --write-tree HEAD origin/<target>`
| exit 0 = clean; non-zero prints conflicts |\n   210\t| 3. Rebase (if remote ah
ead) | `git rebase origin/<target>` | Re-applies your branch onto the target tip
|\n   211\t| 4. Re-run tests | `uv run pytest <relevant tests> -x` | Confirm the
rebase didn\'t break anything |\n   212\t| 5. Push | `git push -u origin <branch
>` (first) or `git push --force-with-lease` (after rebase) | — |\n   213\t\n   2
14\t**Why:** CI runs "your commits on top of the latest remote" (catches runtime
conflicts before merge) and the PR diff stays clean. Rebase here only freshens t
he branch base before push; the merge itself is a squash, which collapses the br
anch to a single commit on `main`.\n   215\t\n   216\t**Force-push boundary:**\n
  217\t- ✅ `--force-with-lease` (checks the remote wasn\'t changed by others) o
n **your own feature branch** after a rebase;\n   218\t- ❌ `git push --force` (
blind, can clobber others\' pushes);\n   219\t- ❌ never force-push to long-live
d / protected branches (`main`).\n   220\t\n   221\t### §3.6 Hard rule: Claude p
ush\n   222\t\n   223\t- Always `git fetch` first to check ahead/behind;\n   224
\t- if the remote target has commits not on your branch, **rebase before pushing
** (the §3.5 flow);\n   225\t- **re-run tests after the rebase**;\n   226\t- **d
on\'t push unprompted** — like §3.4, only when the user says "push";\n   227\t- 
use `--force-with-lease`, never `--force`.\n   228\t\n   229\t### §3.7 After a s
uccessful push, offer to open the PR\n   230\t\n   231\tAfter pushing a new feat
ure branch, **proactively ask** whether to open the PR with `gh pr create` — don
\'t leave the user to do it in the web UI.\n   232\t\n   233\t**Title:** same Co
nventional-Commits grammar as commits (`<type>(<scope>): <subject>`), subject re
flecting the PR\'s overall goal, not any single commit. **Title length may relax
to ≤ 90 chars** (the 72 limit is for `git log --oneline` wrapping; web-UI titles
don\'t wrap) — but shorter is better.\n   234\t\n   235\t**Description must be a
ll English** (same as §3.1.1): no other languages / full-width punctuation / `§`
numbering anywhere (subject + body + tables + checklist).\n   236\t\n   237\t**D
escription structure: use the repo PR template** at `.github/pull_request_templa
te.md` if present (`gh pr create` picks it up automatically); otherwise fill the
structure below into `--body` by hand (all English):\n   238\t\n   239\t```markd
own\n   240\t## Change description\n   241\t\n   242\t> Description here\n   243
\t\n   244\t## Type of change\n   245\t- [ ] Bug fix\n   246\t- [ ] New feature\
n   247\t- [ ] Document\n   248\t- [ ] Others\n   249\t\n   250\t## Related issu
es (if there is)\n   251\t\n   252\t> Fix [#1]()\n   253\t\n   254\t## Checklist
s\n   255\t\n   256\t### Development\n   257\t\n   258\t- [ ] Lint rules pass lo
cally\n   259\t- [ ] Application changes have been tested thoroughly\n   260\t- 
[ ] Automated tests covering modified code pass\n   261\t\n   262\t### Security\
n   263\t\n   264\t- [ ] Security impact of change has been considered\n   265\t
- [ ] Code follows security best practices and guidelines\n   266\t\n   267\t###
Code review\n   268\t\n   269\t- [ ] Pull request has a descriptive title and co
ntext useful to a reviewer. Screenshots or screencasts are attached as necessary
\n   270\t```\n   271\t\n   272\tFilling rules:\n   273\t- `Change description` 
— the PR\'s overall goal + key decisions (summarize the phase evolution for mult
i-commit PRs);\n   274\t- `Type of change` — check what applies;\n   275\t- chec
k only the boxes you actually satisfied — leave the rest blank and explain in th
e description; never blanket-check;\n   276\t- anything the template doesn\'t co
ver but the reviewer needs (breaking change / cherry-pick option / mixed topics)
→ append to `Change description`.\n   277\t\n   278\t**Trailer** (with §3.3):\n 
 279\t- squash-merge → GitHub auto-collects each commit\'s `Co-authored-by` into
the squash commit, so keep the trailer in your commit and **don\'t add it to the
PR description** (that duplicates it);\n   280\t- `Closes #NNN` and reviewer con
text, by contrast, **must** live in the PR description — the squash commit body 
is taken from it (`squash_merge_commit_message=PR_BODY`), and individual commit 
bodies are dropped.\n   281\t\n   282\t**Description must NOT contain** (same as
§3.3):\n   283\t- `🤖 Generated with [Claude Code](https://...)` marketing banne
rs;\n   284\t- `Refs: ...` to ignored/local-only paths;\n   285\t- internal bran
ch names / commit-hash references (no reviewer context).\n   286\t\n   287\t**Pr
eview-verification (required):**\n   288\t1. After drafting, **grep for any non-
ASCII char first** (the CI lints the whole message as ASCII-only via `commit_lin
t._is_ascii`, and the squash commit body is this PR description — so it must be 
