p\nDate: 2021-09-19\nURL: https://github.com/BurntSushi/ripgrep/discussions/1994
\nSummary: 20 Sept 2021 — It was suggested to pipe the regular output to \'sed\'
, or format as json and parse outpur, but it may be easier to implement this int
ernally.Read more\n\n20 Sept 2021 — It was suggested to pipe the regular output 
to \'sed\', or format as json and parse outpur, but it may be easier to implemen
t this internally.Read moreComment options\n\n## {{title}}\n\nYou must be logged
in to vote\n\n4 replies\n\nComment options\n\n## {{title}}\n\n## {{editor}}\'s e
dit\n\n{{actor}} deleted this content\n\n.\n\n## {{editor}}\'s edit\n\n@BurntSus
hi I do appreciate your work a lot, but the reality is that #665 is misleading a
nd not fix or even workaround.\n\nHow about finding some common ground? I rememb
er moving from ag to rg due to being unpleased with project maintenance few year
s back and I would hate to do it again.\n\nThat is not even about my personal ne
ed, as in the end I could write a wrapper to sanitize the output of ripgrep and 
workaround it. That is more about welcoming contributions from others and making
the project more welcoming to external contributions. If people are refused cont
ributions like this that fix real world-usage, they will be unlikely to contribu
te later bug-fixes or just help others use the tool.\n\nAs I was involved with s
everal vscode issues related to terminal, I can tell you that things will not ch
ange soon there. Their terminal does not support hyperlink extensions and that i
s unlikely to change any time soon, basically due to a combination of external d
ependency and security concerns. Some people forget that vscode also has a brows
er version, the one that starts when you press `.` key on a github repo page. Th
at has implications when it comes to links.\n\nSo instead of throwing the dead c
at to other projects, how about finding a common ground and allow users to custo
mize the output? Having a format line should be easy to add and likely not need 
further maintenance. That is even more important if we count that the current ou
tput format is not pep8 compatible: `filename:line:column: message` and that for
mat is almost industry standard for any linter.\n\nI can understand that you do 
not want to change the default output, for good reasons. Still, enabling others 
to tune would not affect/break current users.\n\nConsidering that you would not 
have to implement it yourself and you can have high standards regarding how to b
e implemented, is there any chance to revisit your decision?## hour later...\n\n
I found myself replacing the existing rg alias used to overcome other limitation
s with a considerably more complex shell function, as aliases do not work well w
ith pipeling, only to change the output to make it pep8 compatible.\n\n```\nrg (
) {\n  command rg --hidden --no-follow --max-columns 255 --no-heading --column -
F --json "$@" | \\\n  jq -j -r \'select(.type|contains("match"))| .data.path.tex
t + ":" + (.data.line_number | tostring) + " " + .data.lines.text\';\n}\n```\n\n
I mentioned this here, as others might find it useful workaround, hopefully not 
a permanent one.\n\nComment options\n\n## {{title}}\n\n## {{editor}}\'s edit\n\n
